  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Women Human Rights Defenders&apos; Promotion and Protection in the context of Peace Agreement</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">By promoting women&apos;s adecuate and differentiated protection, the Project aims at strengthening women&apos;s capacities to protect human rights in the context of the implementation of the Peace Agreement with the FARC. The Project will also allow WHRD&apos;s organizations to increase their technical and organizational capacities so they can op&#xE9;rate as change agents, and, on the other hand, to strengthen their role in terms of protection demands with a gender perspective before the State. Finally, the Project intends to make the situation of WHRDs more visible so they can be protected from threats and risk situations.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Update the information for the baseline; initial workshops; training to the RNMD&apos;s teams in organizational development; RNMD&apos;s assembly meeting; participatory creation of protection, self-protection and security plans; RNMD&apos;s training in peace, human rights, protection, communications, gender issues, and self-protection mechanisms; newsletters regarding WHRD&apos;s situation; monitoring report on the Constitutional Court&apos;s decisi&#xF3;n regarding WHRD&apos;s protection (Auto 098/2013); creation of short advocacy material to demand differentiated protection; periodical meeting with local, national, and international decission makers to advocate for the extensi&#xF3;n of institutional mandates in terms of protection and guarantees; international advocacy tour; digital campaigns for advocacy and visibility; relocation of at risk WHRDs; searching for &quot;godmothers&quot; who are public figures; specific protection for indigenous and afro women, according to their cosmogony; representation of at risk WHRDs throughout the protection route and before the UNP and the CERREM; specialized contribution in risk analysis with a gender perspective for the government&apos;s protection route; development of a digital pilot; radios as a prevention and early alert system.</narrative>
  </description>
